WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.420 --> 00:00:11.014
-I'm actually not going to talk
about almost anything that was

00:00:11.014 --> 00:00:12.180
in that lovely introduction.

00:00:12.180 --> 00:00:14.660
But thank you very much, Judy.

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:17.250
Instead I'm going to
talk only about what

00:00:17.250 --> 00:00:20.504
you heard at the very end,
which is this project that I

00:00:20.504 --> 00:00:21.920
and a number of
people in the room

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:24.770
have been working on
for a couple of years.

00:00:24.770 --> 00:00:27.520
And it's called the
Prediction Project.

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:30.270
On HarvardX, it's
called PredictionX.

00:00:30.270 --> 00:00:32.350
Those of you who
know, everything

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:34.590
on EdX and HarvardX--
almost everything--

00:00:34.590 --> 00:00:39.670
ends with X. So sorry, but
it's called PredictionX.

00:00:39.670 --> 00:00:41.900
And EdX, for those of
you who don't know,

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:43.750
is the online
learning platform that

00:00:43.750 --> 00:00:49.390
was started by Harvard and MIT
in 2012, and now has many tens

00:00:49.390 --> 00:00:51.880
of partner universities
around the world.

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:54.460
And it provides free
learning content.

00:00:54.460 --> 00:00:58.260
And a lot of the
content that's created

00:00:58.260 --> 00:01:00.540
takes the form of
standard courses,

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:03.390
like 12-week courses with
problem sets and lectures,

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:04.550
and things like that.

00:01:04.550 --> 00:01:08.230
What I'm going to show you today
does not take that form at all.

00:01:08.230 --> 00:01:11.500
So our goal in
PredictionX is not only

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:13.570
to bring together people
in the Harvard community

00:01:13.570 --> 00:01:15.430
to have a really
interesting conversation

00:01:15.430 --> 00:01:18.630
about the whole history of
how humanity has predicted

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:21.930
their own future, but also to
be able to make the material

00:01:21.930 --> 00:01:26.540
that we're creating available
as very modular pieces

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:29.610
so that the whole world
can use it and repurpose it

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:33.770
however they like, including
people here at Harvard.

00:01:33.770 --> 00:01:36.060
But we've already had
very good feedback

00:01:36.060 --> 00:01:37.720
to the pieces we have released.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:40.030
And I'll show some
of them to you today.

00:01:40.030 --> 00:01:43.930
But just to end the
suspense, the whole project

00:01:43.930 --> 00:01:47.070
won't be out online until at
least about a year from now

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:48.420
in terms of being finished.

00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:51.350
And Judy was correct to say
that I was starting a book

00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:53.319
project here to go with it.

00:01:53.319 --> 00:01:54.860
I don't know how
long that will take.

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:59.000
I'm sure some of you who have
written books can tell me.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.707
But anyway, so the one
last thing I should say

00:02:01.707 --> 00:02:03.290
is that HarvardX,
for those of you who

00:02:03.290 --> 00:02:08.340
don't know the local lingo,
is the Harvard arm of EdX.

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:10.169
And we have many,
many people here

00:02:10.169 --> 00:02:11.910
from HarvardX today
who can tell you

00:02:11.910 --> 00:02:16.070
more about the dozens of
other fantastic courses that

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:17.990
are being created by HarvardX.

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:19.914
But before I tell you
more about the project,

00:02:19.914 --> 00:02:21.830
I'm just going to tell
you what I was thinking

00:02:21.830 --> 00:02:23.160
when I was in Rome last week.

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:23.660
OK?

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:25.260
So I was in Rome.

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:28.130
And they're doing some
construction near the Coliseum.

00:02:28.130 --> 00:02:30.340
And it's rather
bizarre, as you see.

00:02:30.340 --> 00:02:33.030
So there's like these weird,
large construction fences.

00:02:33.030 --> 00:02:35.850
And there's cranes everywhere.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:37.410
But then there's
still the Coliseum

00:02:37.410 --> 00:02:38.368
at the end of the road.

00:02:38.368 --> 00:02:40.690
And then there's guys on
horses-- well, not on horses,

00:02:40.690 --> 00:02:43.806
on horse and buggies--
with iPhones in their hand.

00:02:43.806 --> 00:02:44.580
OK?

00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:46.680
And on this iPhone,
you know, I really

00:02:46.680 --> 00:02:48.180
don't think the guy
needs directions

00:02:48.180 --> 00:02:53.199
to the Coliseum from there, but
he could have a predicted path

00:02:53.199 --> 00:02:54.740
and it would tell
him it would take--

00:02:54.740 --> 00:02:58.150
what does that say there-- four
minutes to get to the Coliseum.

00:02:58.150 --> 00:02:59.956
And we're just so
used to this, right?

00:02:59.956 --> 00:03:02.080
So in other words here you
are looking at something

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:04.190
from the ancient
world and thinking,

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:06.600
well, you know, I could
even do Ifa divination.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:08.080
We have Jacob
Olupona here, who's

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:12.270
an expert on this tradition
of the Yoruba culture,

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:14.360
which is a kind of divination
that actually takes

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:18.110
15 years to someone to memorize
all the poems that are used

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:22.410
to interpret the outcome
of this shaking of a tray,

00:03:22.410 --> 00:03:23.900
that I might talk about later.

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:26.050
But there's an iPhone
app that lets you

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:28.737
do divination on your phone.

00:03:28.737 --> 00:03:29.570
I don't know, Jacob.

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:31.564
We'll have to talk
about that later.

00:03:31.564 --> 00:03:33.480
If you want to see where
the planets are going

00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:34.910
to be tonight in
three dimensions,

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:36.290
if you want to see
where anything is going

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:38.710
to be on the sky, we
understand celestial mechanics

00:03:38.710 --> 00:03:42.020
so well now that we have
integrated all of that

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:43.780
into this World Wide
Telescope application

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:47.630
that Judy has talked about
that even runs on your iPhone.

00:03:47.630 --> 00:03:50.550
This little image will come
up again later in the talk.

00:03:50.550 --> 00:03:52.830
This is an app that we wrote
as part of this project

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:56.190
a long time ago called Take
a Sweater that actually--

00:03:56.190 --> 00:03:57.290
and my mother is here.

00:03:57.290 --> 00:04:02.260
That name is in her
honor, my Jewish mother.

00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:06.400
Anyway, anyway, right.

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:09.200
So you want the weather
forecast with uncertainty.

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:09.700
OK?

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:11.540
So we don't just know how
to simulate the weather,

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:14.180
we know how to figure out how
sure we are about the weather

00:04:14.180 --> 00:04:14.946
forecast.

00:04:14.946 --> 00:04:16.320
And so that is a
weather forecast

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:18.486
that actually gives, for
the scientists in the room,

00:04:18.486 --> 00:04:21.339
error bars associated
with the weather forecast.

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:22.710
And you can go get that.

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:24.910
That might be the most
useful thing you learn today.

00:04:24.910 --> 00:04:29.500
takeasweater.com, download
it on the iPhone Apple store,

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:31.200
whatever, just app store.

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:32.310
OK.

00:04:32.310 --> 00:04:35.880
You could also learn
to do Haruspicy,

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:39.660
which is divination by sheep
liver, that was practiced

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:42.280
by the ancient Mesopotamians
and the Etruscans

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:46.476
and many cultures over the
last many thousand years.

00:04:46.476 --> 00:04:48.350
And there's a beautiful
exhibit at the Louvre

00:04:48.350 --> 00:04:50.141
where you can plan your
visit and learn how

00:04:50.141 --> 00:04:52.160
to do divination on your phone.

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:57.820
And of course, you could check
the projection of Apple's stock

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:58.740
on your iPhone, too.

00:04:58.740 --> 00:05:01.460
Just in case you were concerned
about that while riding down

00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:05.250
the street on a horse and
buggy toward the Coliseum.

00:05:05.250 --> 00:05:05.750
OK.

00:05:05.750 --> 00:05:08.530
So I found this kind of
a very interesting way

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:10.840
to think about why we're
making this course.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:13.410
People have been interested
in all different questions,

00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:16.190
whether they're global
questions or personal questions,

00:05:16.190 --> 00:05:18.930
about what's going to happen in
the future since the beginning

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:20.340
of recorded history.

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:24.416
And some of the recordings are
quite difficult to interpret.

00:05:24.416 --> 00:05:25.790
Rowan Flad is here
and he's going

00:05:25.790 --> 00:05:29.080
to be able to show you how to
do divination by Chinese oracle

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:32.220
bones after, at one
of the demonstrations.

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:35.710
And the truth is even he
who's a big expert-- right,

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:38.200
Rowan-- doesn't exactly
know how they were used.

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:40.950
So we have a lot of
artifacts that we don't even

00:05:40.950 --> 00:05:42.590
know exactly how they were used.

00:05:42.590 --> 00:05:43.090
OK?

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:45.480
But we know what
they were used for.

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:47.700
And so, really, another
title for this course

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:50.750
could be the Past &amp;
Present of the Future.

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:51.320
OK?

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:53.570
Now how did I come--
Judy and other people

00:05:53.570 --> 00:05:56.380
have told me that a way
tt-- an important thing

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:58.770
to include in these talks is
a little bit of background

00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:01.470
of how you came to be
interested in this project.

00:06:01.470 --> 00:06:03.310
So let me just have
a few slides here

00:06:03.310 --> 00:06:05.160
to tell you about the past.

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:05.820
OK?

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:09.009
So if we go back to 2008,
my friend Annie Valva,

00:06:09.009 --> 00:06:09.550
where is she?

00:06:09.550 --> 00:06:11.390
I'm going to
embarrass you, Annie.

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:14.510
So Annie Valva was at that
point working at WGBH.

00:06:14.510 --> 00:06:17.820
And she invited me-- she
now works at HarvardX

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:19.570
and is responsible for
many of the courses

00:06:19.570 --> 00:06:21.140
that I was talking about before.

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:24.690
Anyway, so she invited me there
to be a scholar in residence

00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:27.340
and help with projects
that they had ongoing.

00:06:27.340 --> 00:06:30.600
But she asked me what I
thought the public needed

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:33.080
to know about science that
they didn't already know.

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:36.114
And I said, how important
computer simulation is--

00:06:36.114 --> 00:06:37.655
or computer modeling,
or forecasting,

00:06:37.655 --> 00:06:39.735
or whatever you want
to call it-- in the way

00:06:39.735 --> 00:06:40.610
that science is done.

00:06:40.610 --> 00:06:42.170
And that is not
taught in school.

00:06:42.170 --> 00:06:46.370
And a huge amount of modern
science and economics,

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:50.990
which we could consider
science, and we're not even

00:06:50.990 --> 00:06:52.330
to talk about elections today.

00:06:52.330 --> 00:06:52.830
OK?

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:54.350
That is not science.

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:58.410
Anyway, it relies on
computer modeling.

00:06:58.410 --> 00:07:00.910
And people think, when you say
computer modeling, lay people

00:07:00.910 --> 00:07:04.269
think like, do you mean making
a model with a 3-D printer

00:07:04.269 --> 00:07:04.810
or something.

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:06.200
Like they don't even
know what that is.

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:06.750
Right?

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:08.630
And so I said, all
right, well, there

00:07:08.630 --> 00:07:10.370
are three very important areas.

00:07:10.370 --> 00:07:11.330
One is climate change.

00:07:11.330 --> 00:07:12.990
That's the one I
care about the most.

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:16.070
One is the economy and
people's personal wealth.

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:18.190
And then there's their
personal health, sort

00:07:18.190 --> 00:07:19.774
of epidemiology and genomics.

00:07:19.774 --> 00:07:21.440
And, you know, why
don't we do something

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:25.180
that focuses on explaining
computer simulation.

00:07:25.180 --> 00:07:27.430
And so, we thought
about that for a while,

00:07:27.430 --> 00:07:29.540
and my friend Howard
Cutler who's either here

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:31.130
or going-- ah, there he is.

00:07:31.130 --> 00:07:32.270
Howard, great.

00:07:32.270 --> 00:07:33.230
So Howard's visiting.

00:07:33.230 --> 00:07:34.260
Howard's retired now.

00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:37.720
But at that time, Howard was
an executive producer at WGBH.

00:07:37.720 --> 00:07:39.747
And he had this great
idea like, well,

00:07:39.747 --> 00:07:40.830
that would be interesting.

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:43.470
But it would be much more
interesting to develop

00:07:43.470 --> 00:07:46.670
this 15o-slide deck-- that
I'm not showing today,

00:07:46.670 --> 00:07:51.040
Howard-- explaining how
to connect modern computer

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:53.730
simulation to old
fashioned prediction.

00:07:53.730 --> 00:07:56.450
Because modern
computer simulation

00:07:56.450 --> 00:07:58.800
is just how we predict
our future now.

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:02.080
That iPhone app telling you what
the future of the stock market

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:05.010
is is, just instead of
going out and doing augury

00:08:05.010 --> 00:08:06.580
with birds for the Romans.

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:07.220
OK?

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:10.530
We're maybe a little bit
more accurate in most cases.

00:08:10.530 --> 00:08:13.562
We care more about how
accurate and how well

00:08:13.562 --> 00:08:14.770
we can check our predictions.

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:20.310
And I'll get to that in
a minute when I explain

00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:21.500
the structure of the course.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:26.770
And so let me just also explain
that-- you have a handout.

00:08:26.770 --> 00:08:30.180
So I'm not sure if everybody
has one of these handouts.

00:08:30.180 --> 00:08:34.142
But you, your neighbor
should have one.

00:08:34.142 --> 00:08:35.850
And we're going to
get to this chart that

00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:38.024
explains the various
parts of the course now.

00:08:38.024 --> 00:08:39.690
But you'll see that
it goes a little bit

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:42.549
in chronological order in terms
of the first, second, and third

00:08:42.549 --> 00:08:43.370
part of the course.

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:44.680
And I'll explain
that in a minute.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:46.804
But I just want to give
credit where credit is due,

00:08:46.804 --> 00:08:48.460
that I was really
originally only

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:50.610
interested in the third
part of the course.

00:08:50.610 --> 00:08:54.180
But I was easily convinced that
the first two were just as,

00:08:54.180 --> 00:08:55.730
if not more, interesting.

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:59.220
So what happened, the
economy collapsed in 2008,

00:08:59.220 --> 00:09:00.770
if you didn't notice.

00:09:00.770 --> 00:09:04.067
And WGBH was not really going
to add a lot of new projects.

00:09:04.067 --> 00:09:06.650
And so, for all I know, this is
still on the books over there.

00:09:06.650 --> 00:09:09.680
But anyway, we
didn't really make

00:09:09.680 --> 00:09:13.110
much except we had this
idea to make an iPhone app.

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:14.784
Is John Alper here?

00:09:14.784 --> 00:09:16.200
Anyway, there's
another person who

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:18.760
was involved at WGBH who said,
oh, there's this new iPhone

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:20.550
thing and we need a teaser app.

00:09:20.550 --> 00:09:22.390
So the teaser app
for this project

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:25.190
was supposed to be this weather
forecast with uncertainty,

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:27.710
which it turns out is a
tremendously interesting story

00:09:27.710 --> 00:09:30.480
about being unable
to get recorded data

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:31.464
about predictions.

00:09:31.464 --> 00:09:33.380
Somebody asked me about
that in the questions.

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:35.629
It's a great story that I'm
not going to tell you now.

00:09:35.629 --> 00:09:37.912
But it's why it took three
years to make this app.

00:09:37.912 --> 00:09:40.120
And we wound up making it
in conjunction with my data

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:41.630
visualization class.

00:09:41.630 --> 00:09:45.941
So then one day, Annie comes
to my data visualization class,

00:09:45.941 --> 00:09:47.940
has this idea that we
should turn the Prediction

00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:49.770
Project into a HarvardX course.

00:09:49.770 --> 00:09:51.590
Because Rob [INAUDIBLE],
who's over there,

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:53.720
has been bothering me
for-- I don't know--

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:56.650
two years at that point to turn
my data visualization class

00:09:56.650 --> 00:09:59.070
or something else into a
HarvardX class, which I didn't

00:09:59.070 --> 00:10:01.220
want to do because I
wanted to do something even

00:10:01.220 --> 00:10:02.580
weirder than that.

00:10:02.580 --> 00:10:07.310
And so Annie tells Rob, and next
thing I know by the next day,

00:10:07.310 --> 00:10:10.640
the Harvard Corporation is
in support of this effort.

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:14.840
And now here it
is 2016 and people

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:18.310
from all of these schools,
museums, and organizations

00:10:18.310 --> 00:10:22.080
are now involved in this
campus wide effort, which

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:26.270
I have had the incredible
privilege of leading.

00:10:26.270 --> 00:10:27.840
I have not done this alone.

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:29.506
There are many people
here from HarvardX

00:10:29.506 --> 00:10:32.970
who I'll introduce later who
have made this all possible.

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:36.230
So now let me get-- now that
you've prepared your handout--

00:10:36.230 --> 00:10:38.119
to the structure of
the actual course

00:10:38.119 --> 00:10:39.160
and what we're doing now.

00:10:39.160 --> 00:10:41.160
And I'm going to call
it a course or project

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:42.190
interchangeably.

00:10:42.190 --> 00:10:43.960
Just know that I don't
really mean course

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:45.080
in the sense of course.

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:47.410
That's kind of a
HarvardX project,

00:10:47.410 --> 00:10:49.630
is what they call a course.

00:10:49.630 --> 00:10:50.410
OK.

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:53.750
So overall, the structure of
the course looks like this.

00:10:53.750 --> 00:10:56.630
And we're going to talk about
the pieces a little bit,

00:10:56.630 --> 00:10:57.960
one at a time.

00:10:57.960 --> 00:11:02.020
But I already have explained
that today's version

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:06.150
of Prediction has to do with
modern computer simulation.

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:09.960
