00:22:13.630 --> 00:22:15.270
predictive systems work.

00:22:15.270 --> 00:22:15.770
OK?

00:22:15.770 --> 00:22:18.550
So if you think
about-- if you try

00:22:18.550 --> 00:22:21.340
to make a flow chart almost-- it
doesn't look like a flow chart

00:22:21.340 --> 00:22:23.080
anymore because
we've beautified it--

00:22:23.080 --> 00:22:26.350
but if you're thinking about
how you would start making

00:22:26.350 --> 00:22:29.060
a predictive system,
anybody-- even

00:22:29.060 --> 00:22:31.170
in the most ancient,
not recorded times--

00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:33.600
starts by observing
some phenomena.

00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:35.280
OK?

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:37.140
Often they see this
a lot of times.

00:22:37.140 --> 00:22:38.731
And they start to
notice patterns.

00:22:38.731 --> 00:22:40.980
And then they try to figure
out if those patterns mean

00:22:40.980 --> 00:22:41.750
anything.

00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:43.670
And they come up with
some kind of system,

00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:45.393
which they might refine later.

00:22:45.393 --> 00:22:46.160
OK?

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:49.070
And we broke down the kind
of data that people use,

00:22:49.070 --> 00:22:52.040
the kind of observations,
into four categories.

00:22:52.040 --> 00:22:54.830
So one of them is what
we call deterministic.

00:22:54.830 --> 00:22:56.850
So things like the
motion of planets.

00:22:56.850 --> 00:22:59.422
Or once you've figured
out, where are comets

00:22:59.422 --> 00:23:00.380
going to be in the sky.

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:01.070
That kind of thing.

00:23:01.070 --> 00:23:01.640
OK?

00:23:01.640 --> 00:23:03.840
Something where it's
very repeatable.

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:05.570
Newton's theories might apply.

00:23:05.570 --> 00:23:06.560
It's very clear.

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:07.239
OK?

00:23:07.239 --> 00:23:09.280
Then, kind of at the
opposite end of the spectrum

00:23:09.280 --> 00:23:10.980
there, would be the
Oracle of Delphi.

00:23:10.980 --> 00:23:11.480
OK?

00:23:11.480 --> 00:23:14.770
Something which is completely
open to human influence.

00:23:14.770 --> 00:23:15.270
OK?

00:23:15.270 --> 00:23:18.780
So not even a priest with a
very well written down system

00:23:18.780 --> 00:23:23.590
but really a priest trying
to systematically interpret

00:23:23.590 --> 00:23:26.780
something that seems very
open to interpretation.

00:23:26.780 --> 00:23:28.502
So anyway, that's what
we call nonrandom.

00:23:28.502 --> 00:23:32.800
Then there's an interesting
other random-related choice

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:33.960
which we call randomized.

00:23:33.960 --> 00:23:37.079
So things like throwing dice,
or the Ifa divination system

00:23:37.079 --> 00:23:38.620
that I mentioned
before, where you're

00:23:38.620 --> 00:23:42.362
doing something with a physical
object to randomize an outcome.

00:23:42.362 --> 00:23:44.070
And then you have a
manual that says, OK,

00:23:44.070 --> 00:23:46.290
if you get that
outcome it means this.

00:23:46.290 --> 00:23:48.490
And then the means
this has to usually

00:23:48.490 --> 00:23:51.950
be interpreted by a priest.

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:55.430
And then truly random phenomena,
which sometimes turn out

00:23:55.430 --> 00:23:58.800
not to be random, like the
comet example I gave you before.

00:23:58.800 --> 00:24:00.740
But the classic
example in antiquity

00:24:00.740 --> 00:24:03.660
would be augury, which is
the flight of birds, studying

00:24:03.660 --> 00:24:06.690
the flight of birds-- when they
appear, how they're flying,

00:24:06.690 --> 00:24:08.300
how they sound.

00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:10.570
And just to give you
some example, Emma Dench,

00:24:10.570 --> 00:24:12.290
she's participating
in the course,

00:24:12.290 --> 00:24:15.040
in one of the interviews
